Commentary.Commentary: We are back for the third and final session of the day! The West Indies players are in a huddle with their skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite giving final words of motivation to his players. The experienced Tamim Iqbal strides out with Soumya Sarkar. The onus will be on the pair to get Bangladesh off to a good start. Will they be able to do it? Shannon Gabriel to operate with the new ball first up for the tourists.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

Bangladesh now will have to bat well! They need their experienced campaigners to step up and delivery the goods! Windies on the other hand, would love any sort of a lead. However, all of that for later, the first aim for Bangladesh will be to get past this tricky period where they will have to face a couple of overs before Tea! Windies on the other hand, will hope for a wicket before the break. ACTUALLY, TEA HAS BEEN TAKEN! So, Bangladesh do not have to come out for a couple of overs so join us in a bit for the last session!

They did comeback nicely in the second session but have to say, they are on the back foot in the game at the moment. For them, Abu Jayed was the pick. Taijul too did a good job but Nayeem and Hasan were not quite upto the mark.

Bangladesh will not be pleased with how they went about things on Day 2! They would have surely felt they should have done a lot better! However, they were quite erratic today. They conceded too many runs in the first session and also failed to bowl quite a few wicket taking deliveries.

Then though came the fightback. First it was a brilliant stand between Bonner and Joshua with the former falling 10 short of a ton. A 100-run stand then followed between Joseph and Joshua which took the Windies closer to the 400-run mark. Both missed out on tons however, they did do their job. The lower-order did not contribute too much but did ensure they get over 400.

End of a superb batting performance from the Windies!They will be pretty happy with where they stand in the game. However, at several points in the game, it seemed like they would not cross the 300-run mark as they kept losing wickets at regular intervals initially. They were 116-4 at one stage. They were five down before 200.

Welcome back for the Post-Lunch session. The Bangaldesh players make their way out to the middle. They are followed by the two West Indies batsmen, Joshua Da Silva and Alzarri Joseph.It's spin to start the session and Taijul Islam it is with the ball. Here we go...

So a session that clearly belonged to the Maroon of West Indies. They will be looking to get as close to 400 as possible and continue their impressive showing. Can the Bangla Tigers roar back in the second session after a timid display in the first? Join us at 1210 local (0610 GMT) for the Post-Lunch session to find out.

It's been a tough toil for the Bangladesh bowlers. They haven't been at their best today and have paid the price for their casual approach. They have looked jaded and out of ideas. Skipper Mominul Haque will hope that his bowlers can pick themselves up and wrap up West Indies as quickly as possible. The bowlers have spent long hours on the field and will not like to spend another session in the scorching heat.

102 runs for the loss of just 1 wicket. That's how West Indies have fared in the first session. Bonner departed before the first hour of the session and it looked like West Indies would be bowled out early but Alzarri had other ideas. He has showed his ability with the bat and along with Joshua Da Silva has stitched a solid 59-run stand. Alzarri would look to continue the same way after the break and reach his half ton while Joshua will be desperate to get his maiden Test hundred. He has batted beautifully so far and would like to get that well-deserved century.
What a brilliant session for West Indies. They will be mighty pleased with their effort and the partnership between Joshua Da Silva and Alzarri Joseph has put the tourists in command of this Test.

Earlier in the day, West Indies opted to bat first after winning the toss. Their openers almost kept the hosts at bay with Brathwaite and Campbell adding 66. Campbell fell but that was the only success for Bangladesh. However, they returned with more energy in the 2nd session to pull things back in their control. The medium-pacers did the job for them in that second session with Taijul making sure easy runs were not given from his end. Jayed got 2 while Sarkar managed the big wicket of Brathwaite.

Bangladesh have done well in this session. West Indies were scoring at a decent click. The hosts managed to slow things down and with Taijul getting the wicket of Blackwood, they took further control of the session. They kept Bonner silent in this session and didn't allow him easy runs. Overall, it is a decent effort from the Bangladeshi bowlers in this session. However, they would've loved a couple of more wickets in this closing hour.

The session saw Bonner and Blackwood continue their good work from the second session. They added 50-plus and were looking set for a big one before Taijul removed Blackwood with a soft dismissal. Bonner though has continued his fine form from the first Test and is looking set for a big one on Day 2. Da Silva gave him company nicely in this last hour and against the second new ball. The two have managed to add 45 runs and will return to take things forward on Day 2.

Right! Very good first session for West Indies but they will know that they need a massive first innings total here. Bangladesh will look to strike early when they return for the second session. Join us for the same in a short while.

Talking about the Bangladesh's bowling, they didn't create enough chances. Apart from a couple of LBW calls, one of which went their way but Campbell used DRS to reverse the call, the bowlers have failed to put any sort of pressure on the two Windies openers. In the 21st over, Taijul got the breakthrough as he dismissed Campbell to make sure they didn't go to Lunch empty-handed.

After winning the toss, West Indies opted to bat first. The decision was a no-brainer as the wicket at this ground is always helpful on the first two days. And skipper Brathwaite along with Campbell gave a bright start. The duo punished the poor balls and tucked the balls here and there for easy singles at the same time. The duo added 66 and were looking solid. However, Campbell fell LBW trying to sweep. Skipper Brathwaite then, along with Moseley made sure there wasn't another wicket. Skipper is close to his half ton and will look to put on a big score.

A fine start for West Indies to the Test match. They would've loved to have both the openers walking off together for the Lunch break but that's not the case with Taijul getting Bangladesh the much-needed scalp. However, West Indies are going at a decent click and will be the happier side heading to the break.

Right! We are done with all the pre-game formalities. It is time for the action. The two umpires stride out to the middle and the Bangladesh players follow them. Mominul Haque, Bangladesh captain, starts by saying that they too wanted to bat first. Feels they had a couple of positives for them in the last game. Adds that it doesn't matter if they have lost the toss, they will now look to stop West Indies to a low total. Informs they have three changes in the team.

Kraigg Brathwaite, West Indies skipper, tells that the wicket is a bit dry. Says that they had a team gathering after their win for a small celebration. Feels this game is a very important one. Informs that Joseph is playing in this game for Roach. Tells that their bowlers did a terrific job and they want to improve their first innings score.

Pitch report - Anjum Chopra is in with the pitch report. She tells that the wicket is lush green. Says it is the same wicket where the ODI series was played. Says it is evenly-rolled surface. Feels the top layer of the grass will reduce as we move forward. Says there are cracks visible but they are not completely open. Tells that teams winning the toss will like to bat first.

Bangladesh (Playing XI) - Tamim Iqbal, Soumya Sarkar (IN FOR SHADMAN ISLAM), Najmul Hossain Shanto, Mominul Haque (C), Mushfiqur Rahim, Mohammad Mithun (IN FOR SHAKIB AL HASAN), Liton Das (WK), Mehidy Hasan, Nayeem Hasan, Taijul Islam, Abu Jayed (IN FOR MUSTAFIZUR RAHMAN).

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), John Campbell, Jermaine Blackwood, Shayne Moseley, Nkrumah Bonner, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Kyle Mayers, Rahkeem Cornwall, Jomel Warrican, Alzarri Joseph (IN FOR KEMAR ROACH), Shannon Gabriel.
TOSS - Time for the toss. Both the skippers are out in the middle for the same. Up goes the coin and it lands in favor of Kraigg Brathwaite. WEST INDIES ELECT TO BAT!

Hello and welcome to the last game of West Indies' tour of Bangladesh. It is time for the 2nd Test match between the two teams. The visitors put on an unbelievable fight to pull off a brilliant 4th innings run chase to take a lead in the first Test. They will be on cloud 9 after their terrific win and will be inspired to get better here and seal the deal. The hosts, on the other hand, must have pondered a lot after they failed to bundle out West Indies on the 5th-day pitch. Shakib's injury is bad news for them. How's their XI shaping up for this game? Will they be once again relying on their spinners? We will find out all these answers in a short while. Toss and team updates coming your way shortly.

We are back again! The Bangladeshi players have taken their positions out in the middle. Skipper Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell will open the innings for West Indies. Bangladesh will begin with spin. Taijul Islam it is who will start for them. Here we go...

The game is still wide open with all three results possible! Windies have the edge at the moment but Bangladesh will come out hungry, they know a few quick wickets and they would be putting this in-experienced batting line-up of the West Indies under pressure. The visitors, on the other hand, would just want to bat, bat and bat for as long as possible. Join us for the action shortly.

Bangladesh will be quite happy actually with where they have ended! They kept losing wickets at regular intervals and were 4 down even before getting to 100. Then came the fightback from the middle order and the lower one. First, it was Mithun and Rahim who steadied the ship but both fell in quick succession. Hasan and Das then, with a 100-plus partnership, avoided the follow-on and kept Bangladesh in the game. The problem for the hosts was, the ones who got off to a start but could not convert it and that is exactly what they needed, a big score.

Cornwall was the wrecker in chief as he picks 4 out of the 6 wickets to fall today! A fifer is what he has ended with and he is the star for the Windies with the ball. Yes, he was ably supported by Gabriel and Joseph who were very good too throughout but it was him who was the star especially on Day 3.

The Windies have made quick work of the remaining Bangladesh wickets after the Tea break! Not sure what they had during the Tea break because they looked flat in the second session but have come back strongly to gain a lead of over 100.

OUT! CAUGHT! Jayed cannot keep this sharp bouncer out. Superb from Joseph. A snortner from him. It is aimed at the body. Jayed tries to fend it off but it flies off the gloves. It goes to gully where Bonner takes a good low catch. Bangladesh have been bundled out for 296.
Outside off, left alone.

Big appeal for LBW but turned down. They are not even thinking about the review. This one is angled in from middle, Jayed looks to work it on the leg side but misses. That clearly looked high and going down the leg side. Well, well. A late call from West Indies for the DRS. Not gonna help though as Ultra Edge detects a big inside edge.
WIDE! A Sharp bouncer from Joseph. Jayed does well to move out of the way. Wided by the umpire.
Good length and just outside off, Jayed keeps it out.
No. Here's Alzarri Joseph with the ball.
Slips the first one down the leg side. Jayed misses his flick.
Loopy and on middle, played back to Cornwall. So, Gabriel gets 6 balls at Jayed.

Is that another drop? Cornwall thinks so. Tossed up and outside off, Taijul looks to hit it over covers but is beaten. Da Silva, the keeper, fumbles behind. Replays later rolled in and it showed it did hit he bat.
Flat and around middle, tucked on the leg side.
On middle, Taijul goes for the slog again. Mistimes it but manages to hit it wide of mid on. Two taken.

Floated outside off, Jayed look to defend. It goes off the outer half, wide of the first slip fielder. They go for the run. Blackwood from the first slip position gets to the ball and fires the throw at the non-striker's end.

Tossed up and on middle, Taijul looks to go big on the leg side but ends up gettig an inside edge. It goes to deep square leg. They take one. Think for the second but it is not on. So, Cornwall gets 5 ball to bowl at the number 11 batsman.
Jayed keeps out the last ball of the over. A good length ball around off, he pushes it towards the cover region. He wants the run but Taijul is clearly not keen.
In the channel outside off, Jayed lets it be.
Two slips, gully, leg gully, short leg in place. Interestingly, they have a man at deep point.
Quick run! Good length and around off and middle, it is pushed to mid on. The mid-wicket fielder it slow to get to the ball and they see the chance of taking the single. Make it easily in the end.
Shortish and just around off, Taijul defends it out.

Dropped! That should've been taken. Gabriel is not pleased one bit. Simplest of catches and Windies' skipper makes the mess of it.  Fuller and on middle, Taijul flicks it straight to Brathwaite at mid-wicket who drops the sitter.
Beaten! Lovely from Gabriel! A shortish length and just outside off, Taijul pokes at it away from his body to get beaten.
Flat and on middle and leg, clipped through square leg for an easy single.
FOUR! Poor from Cornwall. Easy boundary given away. Short and wide outside off Taijul cuts it through backward point and bags a boundary.
Floated around off, Taijul keeps it out.
On the pads, kept out.
Loopy ball around off, pushed towards the cover region.

Tossed up and outside off, Taijul looks to drive but the ball spins away a touch. It takes the outside edge and races to third man. A fielder from the ring chases it and stops nears the fence. Two taken.
Brilliant yorker from Gabriel. Jayed does well to block it out. End of another successful over for West Indies.
Wide outside off, Abu lets it.
Abu Jayed is the last man in.
Checking for back foot no ball. Mehidy is caught at covers. Fair delivery and Mehidy has to keep walking.

OUT! TAKEN! Another one bites the dust. Gabriel is fired up. Mehidy's defiance is over now. After banging three balls short, Gabriel overpitches it and bowls it wide too. Mehidy sees the scoring opportunity. He goes after it but ends up hitting it uppishly straight to the cover fielder. Skipper Brathwaite makes no mistake. Mehidy cannot believe his luck. A fine, fine knock but Bangladesh have fallen apart here. The umpire wants to check the back foot. Third umpire comes in. One replay is enough to send Mehidy packing.
One more short ball from Shannon. Mehdiy sits under it.
Short again. This is around the body. Meidy does well to keep it out.
Banged short and on middle, Taijul clips it towards square leg and changes ends.
A single! Islam will be on strike in the next over! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Taijul Islam is in now.

OUT! TAKEN THIS TIME! Cornwall gets his fifth! What a spell of bowling especially today! Take a bow and all of a sudden, the Windies are back in control of this game. Two wickets in the over has changed the complexion of it completely. This is on middle, once again Hasan looks to defend but does so inside the line. It goes off the outside edge to Blackwood who takes it by moving to his right. Hasan actually looked to play that with a closed face of the bat. The drift away from middle did him in.

DROPPED! That should have been taken! Cornwall should have got his fifth there! This lands on off and then goes on with the arm. Hasan looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge straight to first slip where Blackwood spills it.
On off, defended.
Nayeem Hasan joins Mehidy Hasan in the middle.

OUT! There is a spike as the ball passes the bat and West Indies have got the breakthrough they so desperately needed! Liton Das fails to make most of the start he got! Cornwall is the man to get the wicket once again. He has all three to fall today. Das looks to play the paddle sweep. It lands outside off and then turns back in. It seems to have gone off the inner half, then onto the pads and lobs towards the left of the keeper. Blackwood from the first slip moves there and takes it. An appeal and the finger is raised. Das reviews. He then checks his position to see if he is hit outside the line. He though has been given out caught. Ultra Edge rolls in and it shows a spike. Das walks back and takes a review along. End of a superb inning from him but he needed to bat longer. Bangladesh trail by 128. Can Windies take a lead of above 100 now?
Review time! Liton has been given out caught! He has reviewed. He was more worried about the LBW though.
A single as this is eased down to long on.
Somthing must have gone into Hasan's eye! A halt in play.
Good length and on off, Hasan pushes this towards cover for one.
Goes back to ducking now probably because this is on his body.
Slashes and misses! Not sure if that is the right shot with deep point and third man in place! Short and wide outside off, Hasan throws his bat at it but misses.
Looks to bowl it short again but this is down the leg side. Left alone.
Another short one on the body this time, ducked under.

Just short! Excellent effort from Cornwall! This is a short one on off, Hasan looks to fend at it but the bounce gets big on him. It hits the splice and lobs towards gully. Cornwall there moves to his right and then dives forward but it lands short.
Fired on the stumps, Liton is solid in defense.
Flatter and on off, Das works it to short leg.
Well bowled! This is tossed up nicely. Hasan looks to defend but does so inside the line. It goes off the outer half through point for one.
Fuller, this is pushed to the right of the bowler who stops it.
Another flighted ball on middle, Hasan plays it to mid-wicket again.
Tosses it up on middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Cornwall to bowl from the other end!
On the shorter side and outside off, Das goes after it but is beaten. A loose stroke to end a good over for Bangladesh.
One more short one, this is on the body, Das ducks under it.
One more single! Shorter in length again and on the body, Hasan works it through square leg for one.
A single! On middle, it is worked towards mid-wicket for one.
Goes around the wicket now and bangs it short. Blocked.
FOUR! A boundary to begin the session! Glorious! How nonchalant was that! Just eased into the stroke. Fuller and on middle, Das creams it through mid on and it races away to the fence.

We are back for the final session! Still a lot of cricket to be played as 38 overs are to be bowled! These 38 overs can well and truly indicate which way is this game going. Liton Das and Mehidy Hasan will continue their innings. Shannon Gabriel will start off after the break! Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

The Windies bowlers looked flat for most of this session! Probably because the ball was not doing much and they were also getting a little tired. The ball now is relatively new, this short break could well get them going. They would know they are still ahead in the game. One wicket and that could well open the floodgates as there is not a lot of batting to come. Do join us for the third and last session which could prove to be a vital one in this Test.

A solid session for Bangladesh, a wicketless one! They have fought back strongly courtesy the pair of Das and Hasan! Both have added above 100 with the two crossing fifties. However, there is still a long way to go for them. All depends on the two if the hosts are to get close to the Windies score. The home side will hope the two can make use of the starts they have gotten off to.
The last ball is negotiated well! On off, it is pushed to covers. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 3!
BEATEN! This lands outside off, it skids through. Hasan looks to guide it down to third man but is beaten. Not sure if that is the right shot to be playing just before Tea!
On middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Two now! On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for a couple.
That is a beauty! How has that missed the off pole? This lands on off and then straightens just a touch. Hasan plays inside the line. It beats the outside edge and goes narrowly past the off pole.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
Cornwall is back on!
A short one to end! Hasan evades it. Good agressive bowling and watchful batting!
Good length and on middle, Hasan defends it out.
Another single! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Well bowled and well played! A yorker on off, Das jams it out towards gully.
Outside off, Das plays it late but to the fielder at gully.
Length and on middle, this one straightens a touch. Das looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards gully.
Another back of a length ball on off, Hasan stays back and plays it.
Back of a length and on off, Hasan stands tall and defends it onto the ground.
One more delivery on a length and outside off, Hasan does not fiddle with it.
The away swinger now, it is well outside off so left alone.
Once again gets this one to swing back in from outside off. Hasan is solid in defense.
An inswinger, it is on the pads though. Hasan works it to mid-wicket.

Fifty for Hasan! A ton in the first Test and now a fifty here. His side would love for him to get another triple digit score. He gets there by flicking this full delivery into the pads through square leg. The fielder in the deep runs to his left, dives and pushes it back in. Three taken.
Fiery stuff from Gabriel! This is short again. Hasan ducks under it. A few words again from Shannon. Good contest.
Looks to go for a yorker but it is a low full toss, Hasan looks to drive but it goes off the outside edge, on the bounce to gully.
That is quick! Shorter and outside off, it zips through. Hasan looks to cut but is beaten by pace. A few words too from Gabriel. He though has overstepped so it is a no ball.
Back of a length now and on off, Hasan pushes it to covers.
FOUR! Very clever batting! Smart batting too! A short one, Hasan hops, gets on top of the bounce and guides it over the slip cordon for a boundary down to the third man fence.
Fuller and on off, Hasan shows the full face of the bat and strokes it to mid off.
Length and on off, Liton prods forward and defends.
On middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
A short one, Hasan looks to pull but the extra bounce does him in.
Slightly fuller and around off, Das pushes it through covers for one.
Length and on off, Das defends it onto the ground.
Shorter in length and outside off, Hasan has a poke at it but is beaten. Needless shot there. Could have easily left it alone.
Probably went for the yorker but ends up bowling a full toss, it is driven to mid off.
Short again, this is nudged around the corner for one.
Very good stop! Saves at least two! Shorter and around off, Das guides it towards gully. Bonner dives to his right and stops it.
Shortish and on the pads, Das tries to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Crisp but to the fielder! On off, fuller. Das strokes it to covers.
Good length and on middle, Hasan hangs back and blocks it.
A short one but it is spotted early. Hasan ducks under it.
Angled into the middle pole, Hasan plays it to mid on.
Lands it on a length and around off, Hasan pushes it to mid off.
Outside off, this is guided through point for one.
Starts off with one on a length and outside off, Das guides it to point.
Mayers to bowl with the second new ball from the other end! Strange no Joseph.
Good length and on off, Hasan lunges forward and defends it onto the ground.
Shorter and on middle, Hasan stands tall and defends it onto the ground.
Cracking shot but to the fielder! Fuller and outside off, Hasan drives but to covers.

FOUR! BYES! Looks to bang it short but does so down the leg side! It keeps swinging away from the keeper and down the fine leg fence. 100-run stand up, The two are taking Bangladesh to safer shores but still a long way to go.
Almost! Ths one lands on off and then skids through. Das looks to defend but is a touch late in the shot. It goes off the inside edge, past the leg pole and down to fine leg for one.
Starts off with one on the pads, it is worked down to fine leg for one.
The second new ball is available and it has been taken! Shannon Gabriel is on now! This is now going to be an important phase in this game.
250 up for Bangladesh! Shorter and around off, Hasan pushes it down to long off for one. They trail by another 159.
A quick single! Tossed up on off, Das drops it towards cover for one.
Hasan now takes one as he pushes it through covers for one.
This time drives it but close to the sweeper cover fielder. Only one.
Slightly short again, Das cuts it wide of the sweeper cover fielder for two.
Shorter and outside off, this is guided to point.
Fuller and on middle, Das works it through mid-wicket and takes one.
This is quicker and on off, blocked.
Very slow and short on off, Hasan, waits, waits and waits and then cracks it through covers for one.
On the pads, Das works it through square leg for one.
Slows it up and lands it on off, Das hangs back and defends it.
Loopy ball on the pads, this one dips at the end. Hasan looks to sweep but it goes off the inner half towards square leg for one.
Outside off, left alone.
Another single as Hasan now pushes this through covers.
Shortish again, Hasan cuts but to point.
This is pushed through covers for one.
Well outside off, it is left alone.
Well fielded! Shorter and outside off, Das cuts towards point. The fielder dives to his left and stops it.

DRINKS! Good hour for Banglades! They have not lost a wicket, avoided the follow on and are scoring at a good rate too. The two batting out there are nearing a 100-run stand but they will have to bat for longer if they are going to get close to the Bangladesh total. The second new ball is going to available in a little overs and that is going to be their main challenge. Windies on the other hand, are eagerly waiting for that. They know a wicket and they would be into the bowling all-rounders. They would love one before the second new ball is taken. Can they do so? We will find out.
Slower through the air this time, Hasan lunges and defends it onto the ground.
Very full and on middle, it is jammed back to the bowler.
Two more! Swpt on line, it is down the leg side, Hasan hits it fine and takes two.
On middle, nudged to mid-wicket.
This time finds the gap in the mid-wicket region for one.
A full toss and Das misses out! He works it to mid-wicket for no runs.
Flighted ball on middle, MH lunges and defends it.
On middle, this is worked towards mid-wicket for one.
Outside off again, left alone again.
Gives it flight, bowls it fuller and outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Consecutive boundaries to bring his fifty up! 7th in Tests and another one against the Windies. This one is a very important one. Still only half the job done. This is short again and outside off, Das waits for it and then guides it past point again for one more boundary.
FOUR! Welcome into the attack! This is shorter and outside off, Das waits for it and then guides it through backward point for a boundary.
The physio is out! Some stretching done for Das. He may have gotten a little stiff. Also, Bonner is onto bowl now!
Another short one, this time Das gets on top of the bounce and pulls it down to fine leg for one.
Another short one, Das evades it nicely.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
One more short one, Hasan once again ducks under it.
One more short one, Hasan spots it early and lets it go over him.
Back of a length and on middle, Hasan stands tall and defends it onto the ground.
A single to end! On the pads, it is tucked around the corner.
this is worked through square leg for one.
A little too straight, Hasan sweeps it through square leg for one.
Flatter and on middle, Hasan hangs back and defends it onto the ground.
A single now as this is worked through square leg for one.
Chance? Difficult to call it that again! This is tossed up on the pads, it is worked uppishly and it hits the fielder at short leg. He could not react in time.
FOUR! Timed and to the fence! Afull one to end but the line is totally wrong. It is down the leg side. Hasan works it through backward square leg, into the gap and a boundary.
One more short one, it is ducked under.
Slightly fuller than the last ball, Hasan nudges it to mid-wicket.
Shorter and on middle, it is ducked under. This one is bowled from around the wicket.
One more short one! Hasan ducks under it. Two bumpers in a row. Watch out for the full one.
Shorter and on middle, this is pulled through square leg for one.
Floats it up on off, Hasan defends it.
On middle, this is flicked ot mid on with the turn.

DROPPED! Diffiuclt to call that one as that would have been a spectacular effort! This is fuller and on middle, Hasan looks to sweep. He hits it hard. The fielder at backward short leg sticks his hand up. It his his arm and then lobs up in the air. He loses sight of the ball as he is taken back by the impact. He still tries to catch it as he is falling onto the ground but it lands safe. Very unlucky that did not lob up to the fielders around him.
Another one on the stumps, Hasan is solid in defense.
Flatter and on off, Hasan keeps it out.
Floats it up on middle, Das works it through mid-wicket for one.
A yorker now, Joseph goes wide of the crease and bowls it on middle. Hasan gets his bat down in time and keeps it out. Good delviery to end but equally well played.
On the stumps, Hasan defends it once again.
On middle, it is kept out.
FOUR! That is a beautiful strok! Joseph goes full, probably he was looking for more inward movement. It turns out to be a half volley. Hasan hits it past the bowler and it races away to the fence.
Good length and on off, defended.
Good start by Joseph! This one swings back in from off. It is on a length. Hasan works it uppishly but short of mid-wicket.
Joseph is back on now!

A single to end! On middle, Hasan stays back and works it through mid-wicket for one. With that single, the FOLLOW-ON HAS BEEN AVOIDED! It means the Windies will have to bat again. They still trail by 199 runs.
A little more flight given on this one, it is a little fuller. Hasan works it to mid on.
Floats it up on middle, Hasan blocks it onto the ground.
Tosses it up nicely, it is defended.
On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
Cornwall comes from around the wicket and lands it on off, Das keeps it out on the off side.
A single to end the over as this is worked through mid-wicket.
This is really full and outside off, Hasan hits it hard towards cover. The fielder fails to stop it cleanly and a single is taken.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
On middle, Das defends it out.
Floats it up on off, Das leans and blocks.
Outside off, it is not played at.
On the middle pole, Hasan lunges forward and defends it onto the ground.
Quicker and on off, Hasan stays back and blocks it out.
And again, lovely flight given on this delivery. It lands outside off and then turns back in. Hasan tries to defend but it goes off the inner half towards short leg.
Nice and loopy ball, it lands outside off and spins in. Hasan blocks it.
On middle, this is worked with the turn towards mid-wicket.
Tossed up on middle, Hasan blocks it onto the ground.
On middle, defended.
Warrican is a little too full again. Das plays it to covers.

Another run as this flighted ball is pushed to long off. By Das this time.
Follows the couple with a single! This is pushed to the left of the bowler who puts in a lazy effort to stop it. It hits the hand and goes towards long off for one.
Drifts this one onto the pads, Hasan works it fine on the leg side and takes two.

FOUR! Up and over! This is flighted and on middle, Das plants his front foot forward and lofts it over mid-wicket for a boundary. He gets to 1000 Test runs now. Just the 11 away from avoiding the follow-on.
Close! That one almost zipped through! It lands just outside off and then turns back in sharply. Das does well to get his bat in time and play it onto the ground.
On the stumps, the length is a touch shorter. Das has no porblem in playing it off the back foot.
Another floated ball on off, Liton plays it onto the ground.
Tosses it up on off, Das lunges and keeps it out.
Two! Shorter and on middle, this is whipped wide of long on for a couple.
Fires it on the stumps, it is kept out nicely.
Fires it into the pads, blocked.
Opens his body up a little now and drives this through covers for one.
Lands this one on middle, Das defends it.
Loopy but very full on off, it is hit down to long off for one more.
Very full and on middle, it is jammed back to the right of the bowler.
On the pads, Das works it to leg slip.
Outside off, Das waits for it and then guides it to point.
A single as this is swept through square leg for one.
Quicker and on middle, Hasan goes back and defends it onto the ground.
A single now as this is eased down to long on for one.
On middle, Das defends it out.
A single now! Tossed up on off, it is pushed to cover.
Quicker and on off, Das goes back and guides it to point.
Outside off, it is left alone.
A single now! Nice and full outside off, Hasan strokes it towards cover for one.
FOUR! Nicely played! This is shorter and just outside off, Hasan plays it late, he gets it fine on the off side for a boundary.
On middle, defended.
Jomel Warrican to bowl from the other end!
Quicker and flatter again, Das plays it onto the ground.
Flatter and on off, Das stays back and keeps it out.
On the pads, Das pads it away.
Gives it a lot of air and lands it on off, defended.
Tossed up on off, it is defended.
Underway straightaway in this session! On middle, Das goes back and works it through mid-wicket for two.
We are back for the afternoon session! Mehidy Hasan and Liton Das will resume their innings. Rahkeem Cornwall to bowl! Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Right then, this Test match continues to be dominated by West Indies. They are ahead by 228 runs and need another four wickets to gain a big lead on a pitch which has started to offer good spin. The last skilled pair with the bat is out for Bangladesh and a lot will depend on the partnership between Liton Das and Mehidy Hasan. The afternoon session will begin at 1210 local (0610 GMT). Do join us then!

West Indies bowled decently in the morning session. We witnessed some great deliveries from them but it was a mixed-bag effort as plenty of loose balls were also dished out. Rahkeem Cornwall was the standout performer as he picked both the wickets to fall in the morning session. The off spinner was very smart and subtle in varying his length and flight, and looked quite dangerous every time he bowled.

Bangladesh started watchfully with Rahim and Mithun extending their partnership. It was a difficult stay for the latter who worked hard last evening and was once again served some excellent deliveries by the West Indian seamers. Mithun tried to cut loose as soon as Cornwall was introduced into the attack. He got away with a risky shot as it beat the leaping mid-wicket fielder but soon after that, walked into a trap set by West Indies. Rahim's dismissal was a classic example of a reckless shot selection as he threw away his wicket by attempting a reverse sweep.

A fighting session! Both teams fought hard but it's West Indies who will be feeling on top after removing both the overnight batsmen. The hosts managed to score 76 runs in the morning and need another 29 runs to make the touring team bat again.
Short and on off, Mehidy goes on the back foot and punches it to covers. That will be LUNCH ON DAY 3!
Again it's too full and on off, Mehidy drives it firmly but finds short extra cover.
Fuller and on off, once again it's defended off the front foot.
Slows this up in the air and pitches it full around off, Mehidy is forward in defense.
Slower through the air, a bit short outside off, Liton cuts it to point where the fielder misfields and allows a run.
Nicely flighted delivery, full and on off, Das defends it back to the bowler.
Last over before Lunch...
A touch short and on middle, Das gets back and eases it through square leg for a single.
Flighted off spinner on off, Das draws forward and defends it near his front pad.
Too full and on off, Das defends it right under his watchful eyes.
Slower through the air, full and on off, Liton defends it with gentle hands to leg gully.
Spinning down the leg side, Mehidy helps it to fine leg for a run.
Fullish and on off, it's driven back to the bowler.
Turning away from the batsman, a bit on the shorter side, Das cuts but this time straight to point.
Strides forward to a full ball and defends it compactly.
Flatter and on off, turning away, Das gets back and plays it down to silly point.
Presses forward to a full ball and pushes it to silly point.
Loopy and full on off, Liton defends it off his front foot to the off side.
FOUR! Poor start from Warrican! Short and wide outside off, Liton reaches out for it and guides his cut past backward point.
Floated delivery, full and on off, Mehidy defends it back off his front foot.
Oopppsss....this one keeps low! Short and not too far away from the off stump, Mehidy jumps back to execute the square cut but it stays low and beats his bat.
Slightly flat and short on middle, Mehidy goes back and helps it to mid-wicket.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it to the off side.
Extra loop on this delivery and it breaks back in after landing around off, Hasan defends it off the inner half to short leg.
Flighted and full on off, Mehidy stretches forward and defends it back.
Fullish and on middle at 137 kph, Liton defends it out safely to mid on.
A yorker on off at 141.6 kph, Das digs it out off the bottom part of his bat. It's a no ball for overstepping.
Fuller in length and outside off, Liton drives it off his front foot to short cover.
Too full in length and on off, Das pushes it softly to mid on.
On a driving length outside off, landing and skidding off the surface, Das covers his stumps and shoulders arms.

Fuller length ball on middle and leg, Das flicks it with the angle of the bowler and places it to the left of the backward square leg fielder. Two runs taken.
Fullish and on off, it's flicked firmly across the line but straight to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Short and around off, some extra bounce, Hasan does well to rock back and whack it through point.
Leans forward to a full ball and defends it back to the bowler.
The line is on middle and leg and this time Das works it with the spin through backward square leg for a single.
Loopy and full on off, Das defends it close to his front pad.
Flighted and full on off, Das defends it off the inner half to short leg.
Width on offer outside off, Hasan latches onto it and slaps it through the line but finds point. Slightly uppish but not carrying to the fielder.
Good length ball on off, Mehidy punches it from the back foot to cover-point.
Too full in length and outside off, Mehidy reaches out for it and squeezes it to point.

Beaten once more! Back of a length ball on off, angling in, Mehidy tries to punch from the back foot but it beats the outside edge. The off side field is left open and Gabriel is tempting Hasan to play his shots.
Beaten! Excellent delivery. On a good length and just outside off, holding its line, Mehidy pushes at it and misses. Not a great choice of shot.
Starts his new spell with a fuller length ball outside off, Mehidy drives it off his front foot but finds short cover.
Change in bowling. Shannon Gabriel is back on for another burst before Lunch. 2/46 in his 11 overs so far.
Plays a full ball with the turn and it goes to mid-wicket. A tidy over, maiden!
Lunges to a full ball on middle and defends it to short leg.
Slower and full outside off, Das defends it to covers.
Fullish and on off, Liton defends it back again.
Loopy and full on off, Das strides forward and defends it back.
Flighted and on off, a touch short, Liton goes on the back foot and defends it on the leg side.
Good thinking from the bowler. He runs in and spears a yorker at 141.6 kph on middle from wide of the crease. Hasan is equally up to the task as he pushes it out safely to mid on.
Good length ball on off, angling in, Hasan gets back to cover the line and defends it to the off side.
Back of a length ball on off, Mehidy punches it off his back foot to covers.
Stays on the back foot to a shortish ball and plays it down to point.
A bumper on middle, Mehidy ducks.
Leg slip in place.
Back of a length ball on middle, Das does well to control the extra bounce as he plays his shot along the ground through backward square leg for a run.
Too full and on middle, Mehidy helps it to short mid-wicket.
On middle and leg, it's worked through square leg for a single.
Fullish and on off, Liton is forward as he pushes it defensively to mid on.
Beautifully bowled! A lovely tossed up ball landing full and outside off, Das presses forward and plays for the spin. But it's not there and the ball beats the outside edge.
Flatter and on the pads this time, Hasan flicks it through square leg for one.
Slightly short and on off, Das gets back and eases it behind square leg for a run.
FOUR! Streaky! Full in length and angling down the leg side once more, Mehidy tries to flick but it takes a faint inside edge and flies wide of the keeper for a boundary at fine leg.
Shortish and on middle, Mehidy uses the depth of his crease as he defends it to the leg side.
Sliding down the leg side, Mehidy tries flicking but misses.
Angling into the batsman, on middle, Hasan helps it off his pads to short mid-wicket.
Turns it off his pads to the leg side but finds the fielder at square leg.
Shortish and on middle, Das eases it down to fine leg for a run.
Strides forward and defends it back after drawing forward. Yet another successful over from Cornwall. He has three wickets now to his name.
Flighted and on middle, this time Das uses the spin and goes back to work it behind square leg for a run.
Gets on the front foot to a full ball and defends it back.
Allows the ball to spin back in and works it past short leg for a run.
Mehidy Hasan is the new batsman.

OUT! What a sorry shot selection by Rahim! He is done and dusted in this innings. Was it really required? That thought will be going through his mind as he leaves the field. A flighted delivery, pitching full and around off, Rahim opts for the reverse-batted shot but once again there is some extra bounce. It catches the top edge and loops up to Mayers at covers. A real shocker as a distraught Rahim returns. West Indies are ecstatic.

FOUR! Very lucky for Rahim. Tossed up ball around off, some extra bounce, Rahim goes down to pull but it takes the top edge and lobs behind through the gap between the keeper and leg slip for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Das keeps it out safely to end the over.
Strides forward to a full ball and opens the face of the bat late to push it towards point.
Back of a length ball on off, Das leans back and steers it through the line. Finds point.
FOUR! A good piece of timing! A length ball on middle and leg, Liton gently flicks it behind square leg and times it sweetly. The ball races away to the fence and it's 150 up for Bangladesh.
Too full and outside off, Liton squeezes it out to point.
Fuller and on off, Das defends it back to the bowler.
Helps it with the spin on the leg side but not in the gap. End of a good over.
Presses forward to a full ball and defends it solidly again off the front foot.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
DRS time! Rahim misses out on the sweep shot and is hit on the pads. West Indies appeal but nothing from the umpire. Brathwaite takes the DRS and the replays find the impact to be outside off.

NOT OUT! The impact is outside off. A loopy full ball landing close to off and turning back in, Rahim goes down and across with the sweep shot but it beats his bat and pings him on the back thigh. West Indies put in an unsuccessful appeal and their skipper takes the DRS. The Hot Spot finds no bat but the Ball Tracker shows that the impact is slightly outside off.
Slower through the air, full and on middle, Rahim is forward in defense.

Physio comes out and Shayne Moseley is receiving some treatment. Meanwhile, the umpires have called for the Drinks break. An absorbing first hour where 42 runs came and one wicket went down. West Indies bowled some excellent deliveries but in between let out some freebies too. For Bangladesh, Rahim has looked solid in his stay and all the onus lies on him. 63 more needed to avoid the follow-on.

Ouch, that's painful! Tossed up ball landing full on middle, Rahim sweeps it firmly across the line and it hits the short leg fielder on the wrists as he tries to take cover. Moseley stays down and the West Indian keeper is quick to call for the physio.
An inswinging delivery at 136 kph, a near yorker on middle, Liton does well to dig it out on the leg side.
Back of a length ball on off, Liton punches it off his back foot to cover-point.
FOUR! That's a boundary ball. Full and on the pads, Liton deflects it neatly down to fine leg.
Outside off on a length, Das stays back to defend it towards cover-point.
Well fielded by Mayers! Full in length and on middle, Das flicks it behind square leg and Mayers dives across to his right to stop the racing ball.
Good length delivery on off, defended off the back foot.

Dropped? Looks like it. But that was very tough. A full-blooded flick shot from the blade of Rahim, it's uppish and carrying to short leg but by the time he reacts, it goes down. End of a successful over from Cornwall.
Tossed up ball outside off, Rahim allows it through.
Flatter and around leg, Das goes back and helps it off his pads behind square leg. Opens his account with a single.
Strides forward and pushes a full ball to covers.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.
Liton Das is the new batsman.

OUT! It's a legal catch at short mid-wicket! Cornwall delivers a floated full ball on middle, Mithun gets forward and pushes at it with firm hands. The ball takes the inner half and lobs to short mid-wicket where Kraigg Brathwaite dives forward and snaps it inches above the surface. Mithun stands his ground as the two umpires refer the decision upstairs to make sure that it was a clean catch. The soft signal is out and the replays also find that Brathwaite has his fingers under the ball. Bangladesh have lost their first wicket this morning and a very crucial stand has been broken. They need 68 more to avoid the follow-on.
A catch taken at short mid-wicket. The umpires want to check whether it's taken cleanly or not. They have referred it upstairs and the soft signal is out.
Fullish and on middle and leg, Rahim fails to work it around and it goes off his pads to square leg. A maiden!
Hurls a good length ball just outside off, Rahim guards his stumps by moving across and then shoulders arms.
Joseph goes fuller with his length and delivers it close to off, Rahim prods forward and defends it to covers.
Good length delivery on top of off, Rahim blocks it off his back foot to the off side.
A length ball on middle and leg, Rahim works it off his pads to square leg.
Some movement in the air. Full and around off, Rahim is a bit tentative with his front foot movement and defends it by getting half-forward.
Uses the spin on this delivery and helps it to short mid-wicket.
Tossed up ball landing full on off, Mithun defends it watchfully.
FOUR! Mithun plays a risky shot and gets away with it. Advances down the track to a fuller length ball and flicks it aerially over mid-wicket. That was just over the leaping fielder.
Flighted and full outside off, Mithun drives but finds mid off.
22nd Test fifty for Rahim! Fuller and on middle, Rahim knocks it down to long on for an easy run. Yet another useful knock from his blade, trying to revive Bangladesh.
Tossed up ball landing full on middle, it's defended back to the bowler.
As expected, Jomel Warrican is removed from the attack. Rahkeem Cornwall to operate from this end now. 1/18 in his 11 overs so far.
A bouncer around off, Mithun ducks under it safely.

Half shout for an lbw! Full in length and around leg, angling down, Mithun fails to flick. There is some sound as it goes past the batsman and the keeper appeals after collecting the ball. The bowler is not interested. 'He is bowling some great lines but for the left-handers', quips Ian Bishop on air.
Excellent delivery, fuller and on off, Mithun does well to defend it back solidly. The bowler used the crease well on this occasion as he speared it in.
Action replay of the previous delivery as once again Rahim fails to work it off his pads. Joshua fails to collect it cleanly and the batsmen pinch a bye.
Wrong line from Joseph, slips a full length ball down the leg side, Rahim tries to buy easy runs by tickling it fine but fails.
Joseph begins with a fuller length ball on middle, Rahim leans forward and across before pushing it to mid on.
Alzarri Joseph replaces Gabriel in the attack. Rahim on 49 and on strike!
Loose shot and Mithun is beaten! Tossed up ball wide outside off, Mithun gets forward and loosely throws his bat at it only to get beaten. 10 from the over, 74 more needed to avoid the follow-on.
Very full and outside off, Rahim drives it towards mid off and steals a run as the fielder is late in reacting.
Loopy and full around off, drifting in, Rahim pushes it off his front foot to the off side. Warrican has overstepped now.
FOUR! This is extremely poor bowling by Warrican. A short delivery, a very full ball and now a full toss on middle. Rahim wristily flicks it past mid-wicket for a boundary.
This time the length is too full around off and Rahim drills his drive through covers for another couple of runs.
Short delivery outside off, Rahim quickly goes on the back foot and cuts it through point for a couple of runs.
Flighted full and around off, Rahim gets forward and defends it back to the bowler.
A length ball on middle and leg, Mithun uses the angle of the bowler and keeps it out safely to short mid-wicket.
Fullish and on middle, Mithun brings down a straight bat in defense.

Too full in length and on middle, Rahim pushes it back firmly and it rolls behind the bowler. The short cover fielder gives the chase and the batsmen take three runs. Those no balls seem to have upset Gabriel's rhythm.
On a length and in the channel outside off, Rahim covers his stumps and allows it through to the keeper.

Good length ball on off, Rahim goes on the back foot and taps it down to covers. Lets out a roaring 'no' to his partner regarding the run. Gabriel has overstepped again, his third no ball of the morning.
FOUR! Wow, that's a cracking shot! An over-pitched delivery outside off, Rahim leans forward and thumps his cover drive in the gap. The 50-run stand is up!
The first delivery to Rahim this morning from Gabriel is full and around off, it's defended back to the bowler. Another no ball, Gabriel's perennial issue keeps haunting him.
Back of a length delivery on off, Mithun stands back and plays it down in the gap at cover-point. Gets off strike with a single.
Gets away with a bad delivery, Warrican! Full toss outside off, Rahim drives firmly but picks out the cover fielder.
Floated and full this time, around off, Rahim presses forward in defense.
Turn and bounce from around off, Rahim goes back and plays it with soft hands. There is an outside edge but it goes wide of first slip and they take a couple.
Gets forward again to a full ball and blocks it safely.
Loopy and full outside off, Rahim is on the front foot as he defends it to the off side.

FOUR! First runs of the day for Rahim! Too full in length and around leg, Rahim whips it across the line and sends it racing away to the fence at mid-wicket. That went right through the legs of short leg.
Back of a length delivery on middle, quick and on target, Mithun turns it off his pads but finds backward square leg. End of a hostile over by Shannon, he kept the batsman on his toes.
Shortish and wide outside off, Mithun tries to run it down to third man but cannot beat the diving gully fielder.

Snorter by Gabriel! He digs in a short ball around off and it rears up onto the batsman. It's in that uncomfortable zone that Mithun can't ignore. Has to play at it and he does so by taking his eyes off the ball. Somehow fends it off behind square leg, probably off the gloves.
Third delivery in a row is a short one. This one is well-directed, Mithun ducks at the last moment. Is he setting up the batsman for yorker? Hang on, it's called a no ball for overstepping.
Again a bumper from Gabriel, Mithun picks it early and sits underneath it again. He has opened in domestic cricket in the past, so he knows how to tackle the seamers early on in the morning.
Gabriel mixes his length seeing Mithun getting comfortable on the front foot. A bouncer around off, Mithun ducks.
Fuller and outside off, pushed to the off side but straight to the cover fielder.
Very full in length and around leg, Rahim digs it out safely. A maiden!
Flighted and full on leg, Rahim defends it back in the direction of the bowler.
Extra loop on this one and it reaches the batsman on the full, Rahim drives but finds mid off again.
Too full and on off, it's jammed back to the bowler.
Slightly short and close to off, skidding in, Rahim is on the back foot in defense.
Starts with a flighted full ball on off, Rahim drives it off his front foot to mid off.
Jomel Warrican to bowl from the other end. 0/10 in his 4 overs so far.

FOUR! First runs of the morning and it's a confident drive from Mithun. He takes his front foot to the pitch of the delivery and since it's on the fuller side, Mithun easily gets on top of the bounce. Doesn't try to hit it too hard and only places it through covers for a boundary. A good close to the first over for Bangladesh.
A gentle delivery on this occasion, landing on full and wide outside off, not much movement this time and Mithun shoulders arms.
Identical to the last delivery, a bit closer to off, Mithun takes his front leg forward and defends it with an angled bat to point.

Oohhh...that's a great delivery. It's served on a driving length outside off and Mithun offers no shot. It lands and then jags back in massively after going past the batsman. A good take by the keeper.
Good length delivery close to off, angling in, Mithun sticks on the back foot and defends it down to the off side.

Begins with a short ball around off, jumping onto the batsman, Mithun jumps on his back foot and defends it down somehow. An aggressive start from Gabriel. The replays suggest that it pinged Mithun on his gloves, he felt the impact momentarily but is now ready to face the next ball.

Time to roll! The players are making their way out in the middle as we are all set to kick off proceedings. Mushfiqur Rahim and Mohammad Mithun stride out as well. The latter looked a bit nervy last evening, managing just 6 off 61 balls and he would like to be more positive and provide his senior partner good support. All eyes on Shannon Gabriel as he gets ready to bowl the first over. Here we go...

Pitch report - It has offered more pace than in the first Test match which was played in Chattogram. The conditions are slightly overcast at the moment and if the sun comes out, the cracks might open up on the surface. As of now, it looks good for batting.

Losing wickets in clumps has not helped the hosts. After labouring hard to bowl out West Indies, Bangladesh lost the first two wickets inside 14 balls and then a steady stand between Tamim and Mominul was followed by the departure of both the batsmen in the space of six balls. Can they do better than that on Day 3?

It's necessary to remind that West Indies are not at full strength with some big names missing but given the way they have performed so far, that has put them on the cusp of a series win in Asia. Anyway, let's not get too ahead of ourselves and concentrate on this 'moving day' at the Shere Bangla National Stadium. The hosts are 105 runs away from avoiding the follow-on and have already lost the cream of their batting. Rahim is their last hope and how he fares with the lower order will decide the fortunes of Bangladesh.

Hello and welcome back everyone! A couple of days of dominance by West Indies and they find themselves in the driver's seat. A fighting victory on the final day of the first Test has motivated the touring team massively and they are doing something in Bangladesh that teams from outside the subcontinent have found tough to do. A very refreshing change in their style and approach and Kraigg Brathwaite will be delighted with their progress.
... DAY 3, 1ST SESSION ...

The Windies on the other hand, will want to pick wickets early on Day 3. Still more 105 runs to avoid the follow-on so they would love to bundle Bangladesh out before that. The first session could well prove to be an important one. Do join us at 0930 local (0330 GMT) for it. Till then, take care and goodbye!

The hosts’ top order was quite attacking but that backfired. Rahim and Mithun, with a sedate approach are now trying to take their side to safer shores but there is still a long way to go. They need to stitch a huge partnership and first think of getting as close as possible to the West Indies total.

End of a superb session and a super day of cricket for the West Indies. They are in the driver’s seat at the moment. First, they managed to take the score past 400 courtesy Bonner, Joshua and Joseph, after batting for the first two sessions. Then it was their bowlers who have ran through the top order of the Bangladesh side.
Flighted around off, Mushfiqur plays it to cover. That will be it! STUMPS ON DAY 2!
A very loopy ball on off, Mushfiqur pushes it to mid on.
Short around off, Mushfiqur cuts it to point.
Arm ball outside off, Rahim leaves it alone.
Tempts Rahim with a flighted ball. Mushifqur blocks it.
Floated on middle, Mushi pushes it to mid on.
Cornwall gives this one a lot of air. Entices the batter to go for something big and extravagent. Mithun though shows his calmness and defends it.
Flighted on off, Mithun defends it onto the ground.
Floated on off, Mithun defends it.
Nicely looped up delivery on middle, Mithun flicks it to short mid-wicket.
Floated on off and middle, Mithun plays it to mid on.
No run.Tossed up on off, Mithun pushes it back to the bowler.
Floated on off, Mithun milks it to cover and keeps the strike.
Flatter around off, Mithun plays it to point.
Flighted on off, Rahim strokes it to cover for a single.
Floated on off, MR keeps it out.
Short on off, Rahim blocks it.
Floated on middle, Rahim pushes it to mid on.
The light meter is here! Sorry, not the light meter. It is the bails! New bails are here!
Tossed up on off, Mithun blocks it.
On off, kept out.
Flighted on off, Mithun pushes it to cover.
Floated on off, Mithun blocks it.
Tossed up outside off, Mithun looks to defend but gets hit on the pad. There is a stifled appeal but nothing form the umpire.  Because there is an inside edge.
Floated outside off, Mithun leaves it alone.
Gives it a lot of flight but this is fuller, it is pushed back to the bowler.
Floats it up nicely, defended. This one is a good delivery.
Easy two! Slightly shorter, Rahim goes back and cuts it wide of the sweeper cover for two.
A single this time as this shortish delivery is pushed through covers for one.
Tosses this one up on off, blocked.
Flatter and on off, it is pushed to covers.
A dot to end! On off, this is pushed to covers.
Back of a length and on off, defended.
Slightly shorter in length, Rahim stands tall and keeps it out.
A single this time, on off, he finds the gap in the cover region and takes one. 100 up for Bangladesh.
Length again, this is pushed to covers again.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Tossed up on off, Rahim pushes it to mid off.
FOUR! Short and punished! It is on middle, Rahim leans on his back foot and pulls it over mid-wicket for a boundary.
Tossed up on middle, Rahim defends it.
Warrican gets some turn. Again the length though is too short. It is around off, Rahim plays it to cover.
Warrican is too short at the moment. He bowls it around off, Mushfiqur punches it to cover. This is a NO BALL as well.
Short and spinning away. Rahim cuts it but straight to point.
Short around off, Mushfiqur punches it to cover.
Jomel Warrican is into the attack for the first time in this innings.
Another lucky escape for Mithun! Good length ball pitching outside off, Mithin gets on his front foot and looks to defend. The ball comes back in and fizzes past the outside edge.
On the pads, Rahim turns it to fine leg and trudges to the other end.
Full on middle, Mushfiqur defends it with a straight bat.
Length ball around off, Mushi plays it to point.
On the pads, Mithun flicks it to the on side for one.

Beauty! Full ball, in the channel of uncertainty. Mohammad Mithun is committed to the shot as he looks to drive it straight down the ground. The ball straightens up after pitching and misses the outside edge by just an inch.
Good leave! Scary but good. Full ball pitching outside off and coming in. Rahim gets on his front foot and shoulders arms to it. The ball misses the pad by just a whisker.
Good length ball on off, Rahim defends it.
On the pads, Mithun glances it to fine leg and gets to the other end. Just his second run in 38 deliveries.
Bouncer! Mithun ducks under it.
Yorker around off. Mithun guides it to backward point.
Full on off, Rahim flicks it to mid-wicket for a run.
On off, kept out.
Length ball on off, Rahim punches it to cover and gets one.
FOUR! Poor ball and it has been duly punished! On the pads, Rahim says thank you very much and flicks it through backward square leg for a boundary.
On the stumps, Rahim keeps it out.
Length ball on off, Rahim defends it.
Full outside off, Rahim shoulders arms to it.
Down the leg side, Mithun looks to play but it is away from him.
Good ball but well defended. Full ball pitching around off and it comes in sharply with pace. Mithun gets his bat down in time.
Full around off, Mithun pushes it to cover.
Outside off, Mithun shoulders arms to this.
On off, Mithun plays it to point.
Length ball outside off, Mithun leaves it alone.
Outside off, Rahim leaves it alone.
Full on off, Mushfiqur keeps it out.
Length ball on off, Mushfiqur blocks it.
On the stumps, Mushfiqur blocks it.
Length ball on off, Rahim defends it.
Good length ball on middle, Mushfiqur. defends it.
Beautiful in-dipper to end the over. Fuller outside off, Mithun looks to defend it away from his body. The ball comes back in and cuts him in half as it goes to the keeper.
Short ball on the leg side. Mithun ducks under it.
Good fielding! Fuller delivery outside off, Mithun drives it to the right of cover. The fielder there dives and saves runs for his side.
Good length ball on off, Mithun defends it.
Length ball on middle, Mithun flicks it to square leg.
Good length ball on off, Mithun defends it.
Shannon Gabriel is back!
Outside off, Mushfiqur shoulders arms to it.
FOUR! Lovely drive! Full outside off, too full and in the zone for Mushfiqur. He leans forward and creams his drive through covers for a boundary.
Good length ball on off, Rahim defends it.
Full on off, Mushfiqur flicks it to short mid-wicket.
Good length ball on off, Rahim defends it.
Mayers starts with a good length ball outside off, Mushfiqur leaves it alone.
Mayers time! The hero of the last game with the bat, Kyle Mayers comes to bowl now.
Good length ball outside off, Mithun shoulders arms to it.
Full on off, Mithun defends it.
Full on middle and leg, Mithun defends it to mid on.
Full and shaping away a tad. Mithun shows good defensive solidity and blocks it.
On the pads, Mushfiqur flicks it to deep square leg for a run.
Good length ball on off, Mushfiqur defends and shouts a loud wait.
Outside off, left alone nicely.
Shortish and outside off, Mithun looks to cut but is done in by the extra bounce.
Another single as Rahim pushes it towards mid off.
A single for Mithun now as he works it through square leg.

NOT OUT! Mithun is well in! The sweep shot from Rahim to break the shackles. He gets a top edge but it goes over the man at backward square leg. The fielder in the deep runs to his right and stops it with his leg. The backward square leg fielder does the mopping up job. The batters go for three as the fielder fires it to the keeper who whips the bails off. An appeal and it is taken upstairs. Replays show that Mithun is fine.
A run out appeal has been taken upstairs! Mithun is confident he is safe.
Shorter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
Short one, it is ducked under.
Outside off, left alone by Mithun.
Outside off, Mithun shoulders arms to it.

Mithun reverses a caught behind decision! A very good referral from Mithun! He survives and Bangladesh stay alive in this one. Another wicket would have been nothing but disaster here. Shortish ball on the leg side, Mithun looks to play the pull but gets something on it. There is an appeal and the umpire raises his finger.  Mithun refers it straightaway. Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows that the ball kissed the thigh pad and not the glove.
Fuller on off, Mithun pushes it to cover.
Good length ball on off, Mithun keeps it out.
On the stumps, Rahim dabs it onto the ground.
Floated on middle, Mushfiqur tucks it to the on side.
Tossed up on off, Mushfiqur defends it.
Floated on the stumps, Rahim blocks it.
Tossed up on off, Rahim keeps it out.
Tossed up on the stumps, Mushfiqur defends it.
On the stumps, Mithun defends it.
Nice ball and well negotiated. Alzarri hits the deck hard outside off. Mithun looks to defend but then takes his bat inside.
On middle, Mithun tucks it to the on side.
Full outside off, Mithun shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball on off, Mithun defends it with a straight bat.
Full on off, Mushfiqur flicks it through mid-wicket and gets three.
Floated on off, Mithun blocks it to get through the over.
Tossed up on off, Mohammad Mithun defends it towards cover and looks for a run but Mushfiqur is quick to squash that idea.
Floated on off, Mohammad Mithun blocks it.
On the pads, Rahim flicks it to the leg side and gets his first run of the Test.
Floated on the stumps, Mushfiqur Rahim blocks it.
On off, kept out.
Length ball on off, Mithun keeps it out.
The new man in is Mohammad Mithun!

DRINKS! What an hour of final session this has been for West Indies. They have not put a foot wrong today and they are cruising at this stage. The lower order did the job with the bat earlier in the day and now the bowlers are doing their bit to perfection. It has been a torrid day for Bangladesh and they need to try and get back in this game.

OUT! CAUGHT! Alzarri strikes and once again it is two wickets in quick succession for West Indies. Tamim Iqbal will be fuming with himself as he has once again thrown away a very good start here. Fullish delivery just outside off, Tamim looks to flick but his hands are in no position to do so. He flicks it uppishly and there is a catching man at short mid-wicket for this very shot and reason. It goes straight to Shayne Moseley and he takes a good reflex catch.
On off, Tamim keeps it out.
Length ball on top of off, Tamim defends it.

West Indies are up for it and that is pretty evident from their energy on the field. Length ball outside off, Tamim punches it through covers. Jermaine Blackwood in the deep runs to his left and dives to save two for his side.
Alzarri starts his new spell with a good length ball on off. Tamim keeps it out.
The experienced, Mushfiqur Rahim walks out to bat now.

OUT! CAUGHT! Rahkeem Cornwall strikes and gets the big wicket of the Bangladesh skipper, Mominul Haque. Brilliant take from Joshua Da Silva. He has had a very good game so far both with the bat and with the gloves behind the stumps. Cornwall gives this ball a nice air and drift. It pitches and bounces a little extra. Mominul Haque looks to punch it off the back foot but the ball kisses the outside edge faintly. Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps, shows great hands and takes a sharp catch.
On the stumps, easily kept out by Mominul.
Tossed up on off, Mominul Haque keeps it out.
Flighted on off, Mominul keeps it out.
Flighted on off, Mominul blocks it.
Floated on middle, Tamim turns it to the on side for a run.
Length ball on off and middle, Mominul defends it. Expensive over from Gabriel. 14 from it.
FOUR! Another good shot and this time it is Mominul who has played it! On the pads, Mominul Haque flicks it through mid-wicket and gets the third boundary of the over.
NO BALL! Gabriel has overstepped! Good length ball outside off, Mominul shoulders arms to it.

EDGED BUT SAFE! Good length ball around off, Tamim looks to defend but the ball catches the outside edge. It falls short to the left of first slip. The big man, Rakheem Cornwall dives and gets his hands to it. Saves 3 for his side.

FOUR! Good shot! Lovely touch and this is wonderful batting from Tamim! On the pads, Tamim shows full face of the bat and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary. Brings up the 50-run stand as well. This has been a good stand so far and these two should now make this start count and convert this into a big stand.
FOUR! Uppish but in the gap! Fuller ball on off, Tamim flicks it uppishly but away from wide mid on and gets a boundary.

We are back for the Bangladesh's second innings. The final one of this Test as Bangladesh look to chase 231 for a victory. Rakheem Cornwall to start with the ball. Tamim Iqbal and Soumya Sarkar with the bat for Bangladesh.

Right then! The target for Bangladesh to level the series is 231 runs. They would be confident to chase this one down. Can they do it? Or will West Indies produce as spirited effort to get to a series win? Join us for the chase,

Bangladesh would be happy with the way their spinners have bowled. They started with Taijul and Nayeem as both of them skittle out West Indies in 4.5 overs of the second session. Bangladesh would be elated with their efforts and now would want their batsmen to get them to a win.

Resuming after Lunch West Indies looked to score thick and fast but that was not to be the case as they failed to read the lines and lengths from the spinners to fall to them. Some reckless hitting and some good bowling combined to end their innings quickly in the second session.

That was pretty quick as West Indies folded out by adding just 16 runs and losing 4 wickets. Bangladesh would be happy to end the innings here and now would be eyeing the chase the target to level the series.

Welcome back for the Post-Lunch session as the Bangladesh players make their way out to the middle. Joshua Da Silva and Nkrumah Bonner walk out to resume their innings. This is a crucial session of the match as it will decide the outcome of the game and where the match is heading. Nayeem Hasan to start the session with the ball.
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

Right then! The game is still evenly poised as West Indies lead by 211 runs and still have four wickets at their disposal. They would look to add a few more quck runs in the next session to get close to that 300-run mark of the lead. Whereas, Bangladesh would look to wrap up the West Indies' innings at the earliest and then look to chase down whatever target is set for them to level the series. Join us for the second session at 1210 local (0610 GMT).

Bangladesh would enjoy their Lunch after a toiling in the first session of the day. They did well with Abu Jayed operating from one end and Taijul Islam at the other end. Jayed who did not bowl yesterday was spot on as he continously tested the batsmen with this lines and lengths thus accounting for Jomel Warrican and the Kyle Mayers. Taijul was once agin brilliant with his variations and thinking as he outsmarted Blackwood to send him back to the hut. Mehidy Hasan came for a two over spell but was getting the ball to do all the talk there. It would be intersting to see how Bangladesh use him in the next session.

West Indies would slightly be disappointed with the way they approached the morning session. They started watchfully to begin the day but a couple of wickets in the first hour of the day saw them take the backseat. They had good lead and wickets in the bag and could have mixed aggression with defense but the wickets of Kyle Mayers and later of that of Jermaine Blackwood saw a change of plan from the Windies. Though they have Bonner and Joshua Da Silva well set in the middle and they would want them to play their natural game to push Bangladesh on the back foot.

An enthralling session of Test cricket. Bangladesh would be pleased with their effort as they picked up three wickets in the morning session. The game is still in balance and there is still a lot to come.

We are all set to begin the action as the Bangladesh players make their way out to the middle. They are followed by the two West Indies batsmen unbeaten from overnight, Nkrumah Bonner and Jomel Warrican. Abu Jayed will start with the ball. Here we go...

Pitch Report - Anjum Chopra is down for the pitch report. She says it is an interesting one. She further says that as a batsmen you need to be conscious  and they need to just bat and back your technique. She ends by saying that there is still a lot of bounce and spin available on the pitch.

Time for the action on Day 4 of this second Test between West Indies and Bangladesh. It is a matter of one win and the team's morale changes. Such is the case with West Indies. After a win the first Test they are just too clinical in their performance in this Test so far. After posting 409 in the first innings they managed to bundle out Bangladesh for 296 runs thus gaining a lead of 113 runs. Though they lost 3 wickets in their second innings but are effectively placed at 154/3. This being  the penultimate day of the Test how many runs would they add up more to set a target for Bangladesh. Join us as the first ball comes your way in a shortwhile.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right! That's all from the moving day of this Test match. The way Windies started, it looked like the game will move quickly. However, the strong stand between Liton and Mehidy made sure the hosts were not out of the game. However, with three strikes in the final session, the game hangs in balance at the moment. Day 4 promises to be an interesting one.  Do join us for all the action on Day 4 which will begin at 0930 local (0330 GMT). Until then, it is goodbye from our side. Cheers and take care!

Bangladesh operated with spinners in this session and managed to get three wickets. All the three spinners who bowled managed at least a wicket. Skipper Brathwaite failed to get going. Moseley's poor run in the series with the bat continued. Campbell fell in a very unfortunate manner before Warrican, the nightwatchman along with Bonner made sure they didn't lose another wicket.

Earlier in the day, West Indies removed both the overnight batters and took control of the game with Cornwall picking the wickets in the first session. However, since then, Liton along with Mehidy pulled things back for the hosts. The duo first saw off the first session and then they went about their business calmly in the second session. Both got to their respective half tons in the session after Lunch and helped Bangladesh get in a decent position. The Windies bowlers toiled hard in the second session but looked flat with they not getting much off the surface. However, the visitors came back strongly in the last session to remove the 4 wickets in short span of time to take a lead of over 100. It was Cornwall again who did the damage, picking up his 2nd 5-wicket haul in Tests.

A superb passage of play for Bangladesh and they are right back into the game! They needed wickets in this last session and they have got three. Not only that, they have not let West Indies score freely too and more of the same is what they want to be doing on Day 4. However, West Indies won't be too disappointed, given the way they made a comeback after failing to get a wicket in the 2nd session. They have a lead of 154 and have 7 wickets in hand.
